##The rescue took place between the people and the people

Tmagazinechina

Function description, record the changing global cultural landscape

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
This is the last in a series of reports. From February 4th to the present, over a two-week period, we have done our best. There is a limit to this kind of effort: size, timeliness, vision, and even reporting style are not enough to justify our lack of effort. But we also have a ray of comfort: This with the "T" Chinese version of the brand of the cut-in angle is meaningful. As to what that means, there are only two words, records. The record is the meaning, the record is the duty, the record is our justice. If these 12 stories can make you feel a little bit of human truth at any level, it will be worth the trip. Yes, as we said on Weibo when the year of the boxer rat arrived, "if there is anything in the world worth ever wanting and sometimes getting, that is the truth of the world."I wish you all the power to feel and to spread this truth.

On 4 February, construction began on a shelter hospital in Wuhan to treat patients with mild cases of "new crown pneumonia" . Two days later, Bai Yansong talks to the critically ill medical expert, academician Wang Chen, Chen said: (in the Shelter Hospital) to more humanistic care, more mutual help between patients, a total of difficult times.

Patients help each other, ordinary people help each other, people who live thousands of miles away, people who go to the center of the epidemic area to help... in the face of this epidemic, official channels, the people are also a reliable force. The rescue took place between the people and the people.

In Wuhan, where the outbreak is most severe, teams of volunteers such as Wu Xinyuan, Isolation Watch, Wensel and CNOV2020 produce patient assistance manuals and help each other locally. There are also volunteers from all over the country to help people who have suffered bad luck.

On the Sina Weibo topic of patient help, the Name@tangbei Zhang Dingwen is often mentioned. Sometimes his name appeared alongside media such as the People's Daily and CCTV news, and sometimes he was on the road, side by side with his volunteer Teammate@laotao. He is one of those who can bring hope.

Some people don't understand why he can always help patients find hospital beds, Zhang Dingwen said: In fact, it is very easy to do this, anyone can do it, depending on whether he / she has the heart.

This is a self-report. Weibo Volunteer@tangbei Zhang Dingwen described what he and his companions could do in the outbreak.

Now I get twenty thousand@s a day on Weibo. Last night at 12 o'clock, a (new crown) pneumonia patient asked for help, the Internet users crazy@me, from 1,000 to 2,000... . I click in to see, a family of eight people all collapsed, there is still one 11-month-old baby left (reporter: Weibo User@shenghuzi GG posted a message asking for help for 11-month-old baby girl Liu Ruoxi) .

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
At about 3:50 p.m. , I texted back to the person asking for help and added Wechat. We coordinated overnight, this morning to solve for her, in Hubei Province maternal and child health care hospital coordinated a small room, children live in.

It's a three-volunteer thing. Everyone's working late at night. Too many people and things get messy. It's very simple. Anyone can do it if he or she wants to.

Our volunteer group is called the NCP volunteer home. It's not long-established, and it's not a regular nonprofit. Only this time, NPC coronary pneumonia, I got us all together. At first, the volunteers were in a group called "God bless Wuhan, which has me" , we did not know each other. Later, more than 100 people when we realized to choose a name, the health commission released the virus name "NCP" , we took it. There are over 1,200 people on this team.

I'm an entrepreneur, I run an internet company, I do video socializing, I do live streaming. At the beginning of the epidemic, I didn't have so many ideas. At the end of January it was donations, masks. Friends want to do something, (we) set up a "Wuhan Caretakers Caring Organization" . We're all small entrepreneurs, not that big, not one million like everyone else. Five, six guys, one hundred thousand. We need to scrape together.

It was a shopping trip. It was mailed. It was very difficult to find supplies, began to try to choose Hubei Province, can not buy, (on) the national search. Then contact South Korea, contact Indonesia, Thailand, and finally from the United States and France to get goods back home. Look at the Wechat Group of information, choose a more patients sent to the hospital. He was sent to Wuhan No. 6 Hospital, Wuhan Union Hospital..

It was around January 25th that I realized the problem was serious. Was that when it was said that there might not be a "human-to-human transmission" ? I saw in (Wechat) group someone hair Wuhan Hospital filled with people, feel as if there is a difference with the news, go to my friends in Wuhan to understand. They told me it was serious, and I heard that many people were standing in line, standing on the ground, and it made me panic.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Later, I saw on the news that the materials could not be sent to the medical staff in the first place. I went to Wuhan once to deliver them. The city wasn't as tightly sealed as it is now, and Suvs drove up and shipped a few boxes. In those days, the city was more normal, there was no ban as now, pedestrians do not go on the street. It's just the rush of battle when you're in a hospital.

I did not see the scene of the hospital full of people, that night more than 3 o'clock in the morning to the hospital, the cargo unloaded to the back door, pre-communication good doctor to get things, we left. We don't know how strong our ability to infect the virus is. At least, not as far as we know today, with ventilation systems and fecal matter.

I knew pneumonia patients would call for help, but I never looked. At that time, I was very busy, getting supplies, the company's affairs are also more. My friends keep telling me I can't watch this. At first, I asked for help. Each article was a long one, so I didn't read it. It's like I'm on the outside, donating money for masks, and I just do it.

One day my friend told me this story again. At about 10 o'clock on the night of February 2nd, I turned it on and broke down without reading two or three lines. I remember very clearly, when I saw one, a family of six people died three, leaving three critically ill, seeking beds, only one person who knew how to tweet for help. And I saw a man die in the morning, and no one came to take care of him at night. It's bad. It's bad. When a man dies, there's nothing you can do about it.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
I'm in my 30s myself, and a lot of people my age, their mothers are in their early 50s, and you wouldn't believe it. I also went to see a person (last year) in November and December of the micro blog, the family is very happy, take a photo, praise food, walk the dog, especially normal The New Dick Van Dyke Show. By the end of January, life had completely collapsed, and a home was no longer a home. 10 days, 20 days, it's a sea change.

My mother was sick during SARS, too. She had a cough and a low fever. My mom and I were the only ones in the family. I was 12 years old at the time, I don't remember it very well, but I heard that if you have a disease (fever) , you will be sent to the hospital. I am from Yingtan, we are the fourth-and fifth-tier small city, not so good isolation environment. If she's quarantined, I won't have anyone to take me. So [ my mother ] wanted to isolate herself for a while and see if she could get better.

A temple took her in, and I spent a long time in isolation with her. The monks are really good. They bring food and stuff. Now my mother is very healthy, I think at that time is definitely not suffering from SARS.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
For a moment I wanted to be more precise -- I didn't mean donate, just donate. Is there anything I can do for real life? That night (February 3 at 12:00) I wrote down my feelings on Weibo. (reporter: This post reads, "all the contacts will be mobilized... and more people will be helped precisely! I'll dive into the conversation, I'll read your posts, and if I don't see it, I'll reply immediately. I'M NOT AFRAID OF BEING BANNED! Let me know if you need any help! ) . I used to tweet infrequently, once a month or two. That feeling sent out, a lot of attention, I saw a lot of retweets, it is more determined to do this thing.

In this case, I'm very, very concerned about children being left alone. They're in a similar situation to when I was a kid. I was too young to do anything. I don't think I can do anything this time, but I think I can do a little bit.

At the beginning, there were more than a dozen volunteers. On a Weibo group called "God bless Wuhan, one of them is me" , one friend donated a mask. The rest were mainly company partners and employees. I just pull people over, and they start to do it. Startups, where we spend fourteen 12 hours a day together, have a super high rapport.

Patients didn't know what you did, and we didn't know what we could do. We're not professionals, we've never done this before, call and say I'm here to help you, (woman) how can you help me? I don't know. There are also calls to the past emotional collapse, do not know how to comfort, can only say, "come on, come on, is there anything we can do for you" ? We've done it before, buying oxygen tanks, sending masks, helping old people living alone bring food, relying on local volunteers. Some people joined from the Internet, as well as my four or five Wuhan Friends, I put them on a string.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
In a couple of days, the intensive care unit was set up. At that time, we only did this one job. There were 70 or 80 volunteers. They were all young people. More than half of them did this. The rest belonged to enthusiastic netizens.

As the call for help became more and more unwatchable, we were urged to simplify the information, explaining the course of the attack, the family situation, and the address and telephone number. Then came the "docking community" policy, and we established contact with communities throughout Wuhan, using the identity of the patient's family to communicate.

At first I thought things were really bad, and I didn't understand the community work. Why are you dragging your feet? It dawned on me: There was a serious, real problem -- too many patients, too few beds.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
I've had several cases where the community wasn't the same person answering the phone in the morning as it was in the afternoon because the staff had an infection. After such things, I began to understand them. First of all, they've never had anything like this. They're not professionals at all. You can think of them as "neighborhood grannies, " who are also in their 40s and mostly female. Their minds aren't that modern, and they can't possibly understand twitter or anything like that. But they're under a lot of public pressure. People on Weibo are very emotional, leaving messages on patients' messages, leading to emotional outbursts and irritability, which eventually lead to "all the fault is the fault of the community. ".

Some of the family members were angry as soon as they got through, and the community workers were also angry, and the two of them couldn't communicate. We gradually found the skills and awareness of communication. Now, make sure that one phone call gets the attention of the community in as little as two minutes. Make sure it doesn't interfere with their work or cause emotional distress.

For example, if you call, communicate who you are and why you're here, the patient's course of attack, CT findings and nucleic acid test results, and whether or not the diagnosis is confirmed. Focus on patient status, family situation. If not rescued in time, the person may die. Now we can also tell the community which hospital is vacant. The information they get in a minute may be that the hospital is full of beds, and we can tell them that there are beds available. How many. Make a list if you can.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Now we not only help patients find beds, but also do psychological assistance, to collect information provided to the People's Daily, senior organs. The volunteers were divided into four groups, which were responsible for the admission of serious illness, opinion polls, psychological counseling, material donations. Each group has a leader. Nominally the team leader, but actually in the front to give everyone a direction. You can't apply the company's system, such as the KPI, to this. The people involved are all volunteers.

When a patient sends out a cry for help, they're grabbed and monitored in real time. Because I do Internet companies, big data monitoring this area is more proficient, just used in the data entry. Our top priorities include: seriously ill and critically ill patients, military families, elderly people living alone, minors without a guardian, and groups with no mobility. So far, all we've been able to do is make the empty beds run faster and admit patients more efficiently.

My focus is still on the intensive care unit, where I coordinate beds, connect communities and hospitals, and interact with volunteers.

Psychological Assistance is an entrepreneur in Shanghai who saw what we were doing and joined us. They have more than 30 psychiatrists in their facility, friends and friends, and now more than 80 psychiatrists who can channel the emotions of the person seeking help.

The Opinion Group Is@laotao on the way, in charge. The volunteers in the group collected information, filtered it internally, and provided urgent and necessary unified feedback -- as if nothing was going wrong, which would only block the flow of information. The general very urgent situation feedback up, the probability will be solved.

I was on the road with this guy, Tao, who I don't know, and a lot of patients would@me,@him, and then they'd notice each other. He is a commentator in Yangguang. He can speak for everyone. Just like Bai Yansong. Right? Actually, I don't know much about his work.

At noon today, I was helping an 11-month-old girl with a nursing problem, and I spent some time. Then two of our local volunteers in Wuhan volunteered to go to the hospital to take care of the baby. We've got the suits, the masks, the goggles, the masks.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Our volunteer organization has so far responded to 862 requests for help indirectly. 38 people were rescued today. It was particularly heartbreaking to me that the child was left alone and that the child witnessed the death of both or one of his parents. It's just so, so hard.

A 77-year-old grandfather, Liu Li, asked his granddaughter for help. The incident was posted on February 5 and began to ferment on February 6(Weibo User@laosu 8811 tweeted for help at 2:31 am on February 5) . The family, the Kid's dad is missing, the mom's sick, the grandparents are in their 70s, all infected. Just a 13-year-old girl. Liu Li's relatives posted for him on Weibo. It was day three and we were still figuring it out. At that time, I thought of all kinds of ways to give feedback to the community and the People's Daily, plus their posts were highly followed on Weibo. On February 7, all three members of the family were treated.

For more than ten days (coming down) , I felt the change of situation.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The epidemic and the patient's change process is from the initial relaxation, to the people are crazy to fight for medicine, masks, doctors, and now began to restore order in the city. Now a lot of problems are being solved, (for example) the problem of lonely old people in the community is also being vigorously solved. The efficiency of the authorities has also become very high.

In the beginning, many people who were not diagnosed had no way to report to the community. Watch him or her die without help, but you can't help him or her without a diagnosis. An undiagnosed patient can only be helped to enter the diagnostic process. In the beginning, we sent the reagent box -- , because at the beginning, the nucleic acid test box could be taken out of the hospital, and when the patient couldn't get to the hospital, it could be sent to him or her. He later provided information on the location of the nucleic acid test. Recently we no longer receive information on who does not have the test. But there were people who had white lungs, couldn't get nucleic acid, couldn't get a diagnosis if they were negative, couldn't get in the hospital, caused a lot of misery. We suggest that CT should be included in the diagnosis and that clinical diagnosis should be made. Feedback was mainly through the old Tao Group. Now the CT SCAN is included.

And the hospital is doing a lot better. In the beginning, there may be only one department (fever department) . The hospital was in a fog. I didn't know there were so many people. Then came the "receivable collection" policy, many hospitals out of other departments to convert into beds, will be much better. Now there are more doctors and more beds. You See, more than 10,000 medical personnel have been transferred across the country.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
At this point, there's no way we can interface with the hospital. The paramedics didn't have time to get the suit off. They couldn't get it off for 10 hours. This information is published through official channels, in real time, and we have volunteers in hospitals, who tell us what's available in which hospitals. The volunteers included health care workers and patients. Our patient population, confirmed patients, suspected patients, and now the shelter. Patients can also help, they have friends, they can talk to each other, they can know what's going on in the hospital. There are now nearly 300 people in this group, and we have become friends with many of them.

From the patients admitted to the shelter (hospital) , we first learned that some of the shelter (hospital) is a special old staff quarters, the ground is dusty, wash water is not, the toilet dirty. We've all fed that information back. This afternoon we received a photo sent by the patient, the bed in the shelter (hospital) is solid wood, the quilt looks very soft, the meals are three dishes a soup. It feels like a big change, but it could be from a different medical location. What people should have done in the beginning was to round up the houses and make the beds in them, and it was true that there were no hands to do the cleaning. You have to have a frame before you can fill it in. The first (negative) videos and posts that were posted online were basically (because only) framed with no flesh inside. Now, keep pumping in flesh and blood to make this thing look fat.

I live alone in my home in Beijing now. The office is located in Beijing, this is my home when I work. My mom and them are back home. They go out every other day. People don't know I'm doing this. I go to bed more than 2 every night and wake up more than 5 in the morning. Couldn't sleep, wanted to see if anyone was saved. I know the treatment of each patient, as long as the group in the name of a person I know who is what kind of situation. I have always done things like this, including starting a company, to be able to do things on their own point, after all, the things you string together, there must be a sense of responsibility, right?

This New Year I have not had a break, and did not deal with the matter of the company. Our company has developed everything, in the Apple Store and so on audit, this period of time basic also has no matter. There is no cure for sleep deprivation. I'm supposed to be overloaded. Shoulder it. They said what do you want to do after the epidemic, I said I just want to sleep a few days, they said you now every day rest, and want to sleep a few days.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Ordinary Netizens can also join us if they wish to provide direct help to the affected areas. I tweeted about the team leaders once, and a lot of people joined. After you sign up, you will talk about some simple questions to see if you have the time and the ability to resist pressure. We have several wonderful volunteers, with phds in biology, and a strong group of people who do spreadsheets and powerpoint presentations. There are also people who come from a family of pharmacists who can advise patients on the use of drugs.

But Volunteers crack up every day: How can it be so bad? Yesterday, I arranged for the volunteer to be counselled by a psychiatrist. I don't really have that much power. I'm just in the middle of it. The reason to be positive is that the first person might look at me and lose faith in me, and the second person would come in and not expect it to be this bad. The People in the collection group read so much information every day, and I don't think they are any worse off than the doctors.

I'm numb to numbers now. At first I thought it would be a big deal to add 100 people, and now I don't even look at it. I'm sure the patient's experience had a big impact. I am able to withstand pressure than the average person is much stronger, I served in Beijing for two years, this year business almost 10 years, met life, there have been ups and downs. My state of mind is relatively positive, can self-regulation. But see too much or the state of mind will collapse, I did not seek a psychiatrist, are self-regulation.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
I tweeted about the diary I saw. That's a long screenshot I saw on the wechat group early in the morning. A real diary of a girl in Wuhan. It's a record of every day, from the Good Times, to when dad died, and then mom died, and then I got sick, and I didn't know if I was GONNA make it. If she dies, this family dies. After I read it, I felt very, very sad. I also wanted to know how the girl was, but now I can't find her.

The girl in the news who got leukemia and wanted to die, the person who knocked on the balcony for help, including the Red Cross, Dr. Li Wenliang... These have touched my heart. I also see the news of the elderly jumper, the mother because of cholecystitis attack to open gas suicide. We all know and worry about these fairly typical life tragedies. Well, not everything can be solved, and it's hard not to be. One of the words I say most on Weibo every day is "give it to me. ". Actually, there's another word for that. "sorry. ".

I have tons of "I'm sorry" on Wechat. In the morning (and the help object) communication, told me in the afternoon, his grandmother left, his mother left, I replied, "I'm sorry. ". These "I'm sorry" are in my private messages. All anyone can see is, "give it to me. ". Only I know what I'm going through.
